sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_I761009
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: GlucOperon, the next generation therapeutics for diabetes mellitus patient.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: 2007 NYMU_Taiwan iGEM Team
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Combined insulin generating device and insulin degradation device on the same vector.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: OmpR
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Positively regulated, OmpR-controlled promoter. This promoter is taken from the upstream region of ompC. Phosphorylated OmpR binds to the three operator sites and activates transcription.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Stephen Lee, Roshan Kumar, Joe Levine, Ziyan Chu (Polkadorks, IAP 2004)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
The promoter includes the three OmpR binding sites: C1, C2, and C3. The promoter starts at -107 and goes up to the transcriptional start site at +1.
An alternate version, BBa_R0083, cuts out the C2 and C3 sites.
The efficacy of this promoter versus the truncated ompC upstream region (BBa_R0083) or the ompF upstream region (BBa_R0084) is currently unknown.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_I761002
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Twin arginin signal peptide is an efficient protein export signal sequence of E. coli. The purpose of this construct is to allow E. coli export insulin automatically, obviate the need to extract insulin by biochemical method.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: 2007 NYMU_Taiwan iGEM Team
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: NCBI accession number: BC005255 K12 E. coli genomic DNA
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: To combine TAT signal and INS_A, we used two separate PCR reaction to amplify each DNA fragment. We design the reverse primer of TAT signal and the forward primer of INS_A to be complement to each other, so when we mixed the product of each PCR reaction together, than used the forward primer of TAT signal and the reverse primer of INS_A to conduct PCR reaction, we can isolate the combine DNA product of TAT signal and INS_A. (Method devised by Dr. Chang)

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0011
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Bidirectional transcriptional terminator consisting of a 22 bp stem-loop.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from luxICDABEG operon terminator of Vibrio fischeri <genbank>AF170104</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: In the naturally-occuring sequence there is a mismatch in the stem of the stem loop. This can be corrected via an A->G mutation (at position 40 -- sequence coordinate/not MFOLD coordinate). The above sequence does not reflect this mutation (but the MFOLD image does). This terminator's location cannot be found using some inverted repeat detectors like PALINDROME because it is too short and contains a mismatch. This one was found with the help of Tom Knight. It lies between two coding regions that point towards eachother.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: OmpR_BS
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: OmpR binding site. When position behind a promotor, it will turns that promotor into a OmpR controlled promotor. OmpR will function as an inhibitor of that promotor.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: 2007 NYMU_Taiwan iGEM Team
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This part was derived from BBa_R0082 by PCR.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_I761004
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Twin arginin signal peptide is an efficient protein export signal sequence of E. coli. The purpose of this construct is to allow E. coli export mouse insulin degradation enzyme(IDE) automatically, allowing controlled insulin degradation of extracellular insulin.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: 2007 NYMU_Taiwan iGEM Team
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: NCBI accession number: BC041675 K12 E. coli genomic DNA
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: To combine TAT signal and mouse IDE, we used two separate PCR reaction to amplify each DNA fragment. We design the reverse primer of TAT signal and the forward primer of mouse IDE to be complement to each other, so when we mixed the product of each PCR reaction together, than used the forward primer of TAT signal and the reverse primer of mouse IDE to conduct PCR reaction, we can isolate the combine DNA product of TAT signal and mouse IDE. (Method devised by Dr. Chang)
